Experiment 1.1 Contains Duplicate(Leetcode problem 217)
Aim: Given an integer array nums, return true if any value appears at least twice in the array, and return false if every element is distinct.
Algorithm:
1. start
2. Create an empty Hash Set called seen.
3. Traverse each element nums[i] in the array.
4. Check whether nums[i] already exists in seen.
5. If yes, return true.
Otherwise, insert nums[i] into seen.
6. If the loop finishes without finding a duplicate, return false.
7. End

CODE: 
class Solution {
public:
    bool containsDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
      sort(nums.begin(),nums.end());
      for(int i=1;i<nums.size();i++){
        if(nums[i]==nums[i-1]){
            return true;
        }
      }  
      return false;
    }
};

Experiment1.2 Contains Duplicate 2(Leetcode Problem 219)
Aim: Given an integer array nums and an integer k, return true if there are two distinct indices i and j in the array such that nums[i] == nums[j] and abs(i - j) <= k.

Algorithm:
 1: Start.
 2: Take the integer array nums and integer k as input.
 3: Create an empty unordered map mp to store each array element and its latest index.
 4: Traverse the array using index i from 0 to nums.size() - 1.
 5: Check if nums[i] is already present in mp.
 6: If it is present, calculate the difference between the current index i and its previously stored index mp[nums[i]].
 7: If abs(i - mp[nums[i]]) <= k, return true.
 8: Store or update the current index of the element using mp[nums[i]] = i.
 9: Repeat Steps 5–8 for all elements of the array.
 10: If no such duplicate elements are found, return false.
 11: Stop.

 CODE: 
 class Solution {
public:
    bool containsNearbyDuplicate(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        unordered_map<int,int>mp;
        for(int i=0;i<nums.size();i++){
            if(mp.find(nums[i])!=mp.end() && (abs(i-mp[nums[i]])<=k)){
                return true;
        }
        mp[nums[i]]=i;
        }            
        return false;
    } 
};
